ow" href="https://updraftplus.com">UpdraftPlus</a>. <a href="http://updraftplus.com">UpdraftPlus - Backup, restore and migration plugin for WordPress.</a></p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"udadmin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1196:"<p>If you&#8217;re a WordPress developer, then you may have times when you want to advise the user to take a backup. e.g. Before major database operations, upgrades, etc.</p>\n<p>UpdraftPlus makes this very easy. Just two simple code snippets, and you can make UpdraftPlus start a backup on any page of the dashboard area, with a convenient, invisible-until-requested dialog box &#8211; which then runs your chosen code when the backup has finished.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re interested in that as a developer, <a href="https://updraftplus.com/add-take-backup-functionality-plugin/">then here&#8217;s our guide to how it&#8217;s done</a>. You can see the main dashboard panel of <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-optimize/">the popular plugin &#8220;WP Optimize&#8221;</a> as an example.</p>\n<span class="et_bloom_bottom_trigger"></span><p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://updraftplus.com/add-take-backup-functionality-plugin/">Add &#8220;take a backup&#8221; functionality to your plugin</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://updraftplus.com">UpdraftPlus</a>. <a href="http://updraftplus.com">UpdraftPlus - Backup, restore and migration plugin for WordPress.</a></p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:66:"https://updraftplus.com/add-take-backup-functionalit